Speaker: Sergeant
Text: As two spent swimmers, that do cling together

Text: For brave Macbeth--well he deserves that name--

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: Disdaining fortune, with his brandish'd steel,

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: Which smoked with bloody execution,

Speaker: Sergeant

Text: Till he faced the slave;

Speaker: Sergeant

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: O valiant cousin! worthy gentleman!

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: As whence the sun 'gins his reflection

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: Shipwrecking storms and direful thunders break,

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: Discomfort swells. Mark, king of Scotland, mark:

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: No sooner justice had with valour arm'd

Text: Dismay'd not this

Speaker: Sergeant

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: As sparrows eagles, or the hare the lion.

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: If I say sooth, I must report they were

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: As cannons overcharged with double cracks, so they

Text: Doubly redoubled strokes upon the foe:

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: Except they meant to bathe in reeking wounds,

Speaker: Sergeant
Text: But I am faint, my gashes cry for help.

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: So well thy words become thee as thy wounds;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: So foul and fair a day I have not seen.

Text: How far is't call'd to Forres? What are these

Text: All hail, Macbeth, hail to thee, thane of Cawdor!

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Good sir, why do you start; and seem to fear

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Things that do sound so fair? I' the name of truth,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Are ye fantastical, or that indeed

Text: Which outwardly ye show? My noble partner

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Of noble having and of royal hope,

Speaker: BANQUO

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Stay, you imperfect speakers, tell me more:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: By Sinel's death I know I am thane of Glamis;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But how of Cawdor? the thane of Cawdor lives,

Text: Stands not within the prospect of belief,

Text: You owe this strange intelligence? or why

Speaker: MACBETH

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Witches vanish.

Text: The earth hath bubbles, as the water has,

Text: O worthiest cousin!

Text: Welcome hither:

Text: The Prince of Cumberland! that is a step

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: 'They met me in the day of success: and I have

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: learned by the perfectest report, they have more in

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: them than mortal knowledge. When I burned in desire

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: to question them further, they made themselves air,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: into which they vanished. Whiles I stood rapt in

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: the wonder of it, came missivesfrom the king, who

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: all-hailed me 'Thane of Cawdor;' by which title,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: before, these weird sisters saluted me, and referred

Speaker: LADY MACBETH

Text: shalt be!' This have I thought good to deliver

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: thee, my dearest partner of greatness, that thou

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: mightst not lose the dues of rejoicing, by being

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: ignorant of what greatness is promised thee. Lay it

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: to thy heart, and farewell.'

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Glamis thou art, and Cawdor; and shalt be

Text: What thou art promised: yet do I fear thy nature;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: To catch the nearest way: thou wouldst be great;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Art not without ambition, but without

Speaker: LADY MACBETH

Speaker: LADY MACBETH

Text: The effect and it! Come to my woman's breasts,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And take my milk for gall, you murdering ministers,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Wherever in your sightless substances

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: You wait on nature's mischief! Come, thick night,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And pall thee in the dunnest smoke of hell,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: That my keen knife see not the wound it makes,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Nor heaven peep through the blanket of the dark,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: To cry 'Hold, hold!'

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Great Glamis! worthy Cawdor!

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Greater than both, by the all-hail hereafter!

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Thy letters have transported me beyond

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: This ignorant present, and I feel now

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: The future in the instant.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: My dearest love,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Duncan comes here to-night.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And when goes hence?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To-morrow, as he purposes.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: O, never

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Shall sun that morrow see!

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Your face, my thane, is as a book where men

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: May read strange matters. To beguile the time,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Look like the time; bear welcome in your eye,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Your hand, your tongue: look like the innocent flower,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: But be the serpent under't. He that's coming

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Must be provided for: and you shall put

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: This night's great business into my dispatch;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Which shall to all our nights and days to come

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Give solely sovereign sway and masterdom.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: We will speak further.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Only look up clear;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: To alter favour ever is to fear:

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Leave all the rest to me.

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: This castle hath a pleasant seat; the air

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: Nimbly and sweetly recommends itself

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: Unto our gentle senses.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: This guest of summer,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: The temple-haunting martlet does approve,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: By his loved mansionry, that the heaven's breath

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Smells wooingly here: no jutty, frieze,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Buttress, nor coign of vantage, but this bird

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Hath made his pendent bed and procreant cradle:

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Where they most breed and haunt, I have observed,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: The air is delicate.

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: See, see our honoured hostess!

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: The love that follows us sometime is our trouble,

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: Which still we thank as love. Herein I teach you

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: How you shall bid God 'ild us for your pains,

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: And thank us for your trouble.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: All our service

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: In every point twice done and then done double

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Were poor and single business to contend

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Against those honours deep and broad wherewith

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Your majesty loads our house: for those of old,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And the late dignities heap'd up to them,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: We rest your hermits.

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: Where's the thane of Cawdor?

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: We coursed him at the heels, and had a purpose

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: To be his purveyor: but he rides well;

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: And his great love, sharp as his spur, hath holp him

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: To his home before us. Fair and noble hostess,

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: We are your guest to-night.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Your servants ever

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Have theirs, themselves and what is theirs, in compt,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: To make their audit at your highness' pleasure,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Still to return your own.

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: Give me your hand;

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: Conduct me to mine host: we love him highly,

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: And shall continue our graces towards him.

Speaker: DUNCAN
Text: By your leave, hostess.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: If it were done when 'tis done, then 'twere well

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: It were done quickly: if the assassination

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Could trammel up the consequence, and catch

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: With his surcease success; that but this blow

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Might be the be-all and the end-all here,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But here, upon this bank and shoal of time,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: We'ld jump the life to come. But in these cases

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: We still have judgment here;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: that we but teach

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Bloody instructions, which, being taught, return

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To plague the inventor:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: this even-handed justice

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Commends the ingredience of our poison'd chalice

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To our own lips. He's here in double trust;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: First, as I am his kinsman and his subject,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Strong both against the deed; then, as his host,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Who should against his murderer shut the door,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Not bear the knife myself. Besides, this Duncan

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Hath borne his faculties so meek, hath been

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: So clear in his great office, that his virtues

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Will plead like angels, trumpet-tongued, against

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The deep damnation of his taking-off;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And pity, like a naked new-born babe,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Striding the blast, or heaven's cherubim, horsed

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Upon the sightless couriers of the air,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Shall blow the horrid deed in every eye,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That tears shall drown the wind. I have no spur

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To prick the sides of my intent, but only

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Vaulting ambition, which o'erleaps itself

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And falls on th'other.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: How now! what news?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: He has almost supp'd: why have you left the chamber?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Hath he ask'd for me?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Know you not he has?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: We will proceed no further in this business:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: He hath honour'd me of late; and I have bought

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Golden opinions from all sorts of people,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Which would be worn now in their newest gloss,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Not cast aside so soon.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Was the hope drunk

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Wherein you dress'd yourself? hath it slept since?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And wakes it now, to look so green and pale

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: At what it did so freely? From this time

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Such I account thy love. Art thou afeard

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: To be the same in thine own act and valour

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: As thou art in desire? Wouldst thou have that

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Which thou esteem'st the ornament of life,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And live a coward in thine own esteem,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Letting 'I dare not' wait upon 'I would,'

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Like the poor cat i' the adage?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Prithee, peace:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I dare do all that may become a man;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Who dares do more is none.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: What beast was't, then,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: That made you break this enterprise to me?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: When you durst do it, then you were a man;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And, to be more than what you were, you would

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Be so much more the man. Nor time nor place

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Did then adhere, and yet you would make both:

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: They have made themselves, and that their fitness now

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Does unmake you. I have given suck, and know

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: How tender 'tis to love the babe that milks me:

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: I would, while it was smiling in my face,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Have pluck'd my nipple from his boneless gums,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And dash'd the brains out, had I so sworn as you

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Have done to this.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: If we should fail?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: We fail!

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: But screw your courage to the sticking-place,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And we'll not fail. When Duncan is asleep--

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Whereto the rather shall his day's hard journey

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Soundly invite him--his two chamberlains

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Will I with wine and wassail so convince

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: That memory, the warder of the brain,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Shall be a fume, and the receipt of reason

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: A limbeck only: when in swinish sleep

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Their drenched natures lie as in a death,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: What cannot you and I perform upon

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: The unguarded Duncan? what not put upon

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: His spongy officers, who shall bear the guilt

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Of our great quell?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Bring forth men-children only;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: For thy undaunted mettle should compose

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Nothing but males. Will it not be received,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: When we have mark'd with blood those sleepy two

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Of his own chamber and used their very daggers,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That they have done't?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Who dares receive it other,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: As we shall make our griefs and clamour roar

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Upon his death?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I am settled, and bend up

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Each corporal agent to this terrible feat.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Away, and mock the time with fairest show:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: False face must hide what the false heart doth know.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: How goes the night, boy?

Speaker: FLEANCE
Text: The moon is down; I have not heard the clock.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: And she goes down at twelve.

Speaker: FLEANCE
Text: I take't, 'tis later, sir.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Hold, take my sword. There's husbandry in heaven;

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Their candles are all out. Take thee that too.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: A heavy summons lies like lead upon me,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: And yet I would not sleep: merciful powers,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Restrain in me the cursed thoughts that nature

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Gives way to in repose!

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Give me my sword.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Who's there?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: A friend.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: What, sir, not yet at rest? The king's a-bed:

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: He hath been in unusual pleasure, and

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Sent forth great largess to your offices.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: This diamond he greets your wife withal,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: By the name of most kind hostess; and shut up

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: In measureless content.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Being unprepared

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Our will became the servant to defect

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Which else should free have wrought.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: All's well.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: I dreamt last night of the three weird sisters:

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: To you they have show'd some truth.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I think not of them:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Yet, when we can entreat an hour to serve,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: We would spend it in some words upon that business,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: If you would grant the time.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: At your kind'st leisure.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: If you shall cleave to my consent, when 'tis,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: It shall make honour for you.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: So I lose none

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: In seeking to augment it, but still keep

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: My bosom franchised and allegiance clear,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: I shall be counsell'd.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Good repose the while!

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Thanks, sir: the like to you!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Go bid thy mistress, when my drink is ready,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: She strike upon the bell. Get thee to bed.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Is this a dagger which I see before me,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The handle toward my hand? Come, let me clutch thee.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I have thee not, and yet I see thee still.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Art thou not, fatal vision, sensible

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To feeling as to sight? or art thou but

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: A dagger of the mind, a false creation,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Proceeding from the heat-oppressed brain?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I see thee yet, in form as palpable

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: As this which now I draw.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thou marshall'st me the way that I was going;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And such an instrument I was to use.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Mine eyes are made the fools o' the other senses,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Or else worth all the rest; I see thee still,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And on thy blade and dudgeon gouts of blood,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Which was not so before. There's no such thing:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: It is the bloody business which informs

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thus to mine eyes. Now o'er the one halfworld

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Nature seems dead, and wicked dreams abuse

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The curtain'd sleep; witchcraft celebrates

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Pale Hecate's offerings, and wither'd murder,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Alarum'd by his sentinel, the wolf,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Whose howl's his watch, thus with his stealthy pace.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: With Tarquin's ravishing strides, towards his design

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Moves like a ghost. Thou sure and firm-set earth,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Hear not my steps, which way they walk, for fear

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thy very stones prate of my whereabout,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And take the present horror from the time,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Which now suits with it. Whiles I threat, he lives:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Words to the heat of deeds too cold breath gives.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I go, and it is done; the bell invites me.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Hear it not, Duncan; for it is a knell

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That summons thee to heaven or to hell.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: That which hath made them drunk hath made me bold;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: What hath quench'd them hath given me fire.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Hark! Peace!

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: It was the owl that shriek'd, the fatal bellman,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Which gives the stern'st good-night. He is about it:

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: The doors are open; and the surfeited grooms

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Do mock their charge with snores: I have drugg'd

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: their possets,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: That death and nature do contend about them,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Whether they live or die.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Who's there? what, ho!

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Alack, I am afraid they have awaked,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And 'tis not done. The attempt and not the deed

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Confounds us. Hark! I laid their daggers ready;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: He could not miss 'em. Had he not resembled

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: My father as he slept, I had done't.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: My husband!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I have done the deed. Didst thou not hear a noise?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: I heard the owl scream and the crickets cry.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Did not you speak?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: When?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Now.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: As I descended?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Ay.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Hark!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Who lies i' the second chamber?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Donalbain.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: This is a sorry sight.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: A foolish thought, to say a sorry sight.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: There's one did laugh in's sleep, and one cried

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: 'Murder!'

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That they did wake each other: I stood and heard them:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But they did say their prayers, and address'd them

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Again to sleep.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: There are two lodged together.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: One cried 'God bless us!' and 'Amen' the other;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: As they had seen me with these hangman's hands.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Listening their fear, I could not say 'Amen,'

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: When they did say 'God bless us!'

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Consider it not so deeply.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But wherefore could not I pronounce 'Amen'?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I had most need of blessing, and 'Amen'

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Stuck in my throat.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: These deeds must not be thought

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: After these ways; so, it will make us mad.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Methought I heard a voice cry 'Sleep no more!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Macbeth does murder sleep', the innocent sleep,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Sleep that knits up the ravell'd sleeve of care,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The death of each day's life, sore labour's bath,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Balm of hurt minds, great nature's second course,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Chief nourisher in life's feast,--

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: What do you mean?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Still it cried 'Sleep no more!' to all the house:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: 'Glamis hath murder'd sleep, and therefore Cawdor

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Shall sleep no more; Macbeth shall sleep no more.'

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Who was it that thus cried? Why, worthy thane,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: You do unbend your noble strength, to think

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: So brainsickly of things. Go get some water,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And wash this filthy witness from your hand.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Why did you bring these daggers from the place?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: They must lie there: go carry them; and smear

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: The sleepy grooms with blood.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I'll go no more:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I am afraid to think what I have done;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Look on't again I dare not.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Infirm of purpose!

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Give me the daggers: the sleeping and the dead

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Are but as pictures: 'tis the eye of childhood

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: That fears a painted devil. If he do bleed,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: I'll gild the faces of the grooms withal;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: For it must seem their guilt.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Whence is that knocking?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: How is't with me, when every noise appals me?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What hands are here? ha! they pluck out mine eyes.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Will all great Neptune's ocean wash this blood

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Clean from my hand? No, this my hand will rather

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The multitudinous seas in incarnadine,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Making the green one red.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: My hands are of your colour; but I shame

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: To wear a heart so white.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: I hear a knocking

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: At the south entry: retire we to our chamber;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: A little water clears us of this deed:

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: How easy is it, then! Your constancy

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Hath left you unattended.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Hark! more knocking.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Get on your nightgown, lest occasion call us,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: And show us to be watchers. Be not lost

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: So poorly in your thoughts.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To know my deed, 'twere best not know myself.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Wake Duncan with thy knocking! I would thou couldst!

Speaker: PORTER
Text: Here's a knocking indeed! If a

Speaker: PORTER
Text: man were porter of hell-gate, he should have

Speaker: PORTER
Text: old turning the key.

Speaker: PORTER
Text: Knock,

Speaker: PORTER
Text: knock, knock! Who's there, i' the name of

Speaker: PORTER
Text: Beelzebub? Here's a farmer, that hanged

Speaker: PORTER
Text: himself on the expectation of plenty: come in

Speaker: PORTER
Text: time; have napkins enow about you; here

Speaker: PORTER
Text: you'll sweat for't.

Speaker: PORTER
Text: Knock,

Speaker: PORTER
Text: knock! Who's there, in the other devil's

Speaker: PORTER
Text: name? Faith, here's an equivocator, that could

Speaker: PORTER
Text: swear in both the scales against either scale;

Speaker: PORTER
Text: who committed treason enough for God's sake,

Speaker: PORTER
Text: yet could not equivocate to heaven: O, come

Speaker: PORTER
Text: in, equivocator.

Speaker: PORTER
Text: Knock,

Speaker: PORTER
Text: knock, knock! Who's there? Faith, here's an

Speaker: PORTER
Text: English tailor come hither, for stealing out of

Speaker: PORTER
Text: a French hose: come in, tailor; here you may

Speaker: PORTER
Text: roast your goose.

Speaker: PORTER
Text: Knock,

Speaker: PORTER
Text: knock; never at quiet! What are you? But

Speaker: PORTER
Text: this place is too cold for hell. I'll devil-porter

Speaker: PORTER
Text: it no further: I had thought to have let in

Speaker: PORTER
Text: some of all professions that go the primrose

Speaker: PORTER
Text: way to the everlasting bonfire.

Speaker: PORTER
Text: Anon, anon! I pray you, remember the porter.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Was it so late, friend, ere you went to bed,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: That you do lie so late?

Speaker: Porter
Text: 'Faith sir, we were carousing till the second cock: and drink, sir, is a great provoker of three things.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: What three things does drink especially provoke?

Speaker: Porter
Text: Marry, sir, nose-painting, sleep, and

Speaker: Porter
Text: urine. Lechery, sir, it provokes, and unprovokes;

Speaker: Porter
Text: it provokes the desire, but it takes

Speaker: Porter
Text: away the performance: therefore, much drink

Speaker: Porter
Text: may be said to be an equivocator with lechery:

Speaker: Porter
Text: it makes him, and it mars him; it sets

Speaker: Porter
Text: him on, and it takes him off; it persuades him,

Speaker: Porter
Text: and disheartens him; makes him stand to, and

Speaker: Porter
Text: not stand to; in conclusion, equivocates him

Speaker: Porter
Text: in a sleep, and, giving him the lie, leaves him.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I believe drink gave thee the lie last night.

Speaker: Porter
Text: That it did, sir, i' the very throat on

Speaker: Porter
Text: me: but I requited him for his lie; and, I

Speaker: Porter
Text: think, being too strong for him, though he took

Speaker: Porter
Text: up my legs sometime, yet I made a shift to cast

Speaker: Porter
Text: him.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Is thy master stirring?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Our knocking has awaked him; here he comes.

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Good morrow, noble sir.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Good morrow, both.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Is the king stirring, worthy thane?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Not yet.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: He did command me to call timely on him:

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I have almost slipp'd the hour.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I'll bring you to him.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I know this is a joyful trouble to you;

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: But yet 'tis one.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The labour we delight in physics pain.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: This is the door.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I'll make so bold to call,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: For 'tis my limited service.

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Goes the king hence to-day?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: He does: he did appoint so.

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: The night has been unruly: where we lay,

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Our chimneys were blown down; and, as they say,

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Lamentings heard i' the air; strange screams of death,

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: And prophesying with accents terrible

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Of dire combustion and confused events

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: New hatch'd to the woeful time: the obscure bird

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Clamour'd the livelong night: some say, the earth

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Was feverous and did shake.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: 'Twas a rough night.

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: My young remembrance cannot parallel

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: A fellow to it.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: O horror, horror, horror! Tongue nor heart

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Cannot conceive nor name thee!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What's the matter>

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Confusion now hath made his masterpiece!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Most sacrilegious murder hath broke ope

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The Lord's anointed temple, and stole thence

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The life o' the building!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What is 't you say? the life?

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Mean you his majesty?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Approach the chamber, and destroy your sight

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: With a new Gorgon: do not bid me speak;

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: See, and then speak yourselves.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Awake, awake!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Ring the alarum-bell. Murder and treason!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Banquo and Donalbain! Malcolm! awake!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Shake off this downy sleep, death's counterfeit,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And look on death itself! up, up, and see

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The great doom's image! Malcolm! Banquo!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: As from your graves rise up, and walk like sprites,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: To countenance this horror! Ring the bell.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: What's the business,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: That such a hideous trumpet calls to parley

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: The sleepers of the house? speak, speak!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: O gentle lady,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: 'Tis not for you to hear what I can speak:

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The repetition, in a woman's ear,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Would murder as it fell.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: O Banquo, Banquo,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Our royal master 's murder'd!

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Woe, alas!

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: What, in our house?

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Too cruel any where.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Dear Duff, I prithee, contradict thyself,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: And say it is not so.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Had I but died an hour before this chance,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I had lived a blessed time; for, from this instant,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: There 's nothing serious in mortality:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: All is but toys: renown and grace is dead;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The wine of life is drawn, and the mere lees

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Is left this vault to brag of.

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: What is amiss?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: You are, and do not know't:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The spring, the head, the fountain of your blood

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Is stopp'd; the very source of it is stopp'd.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Your royal father 's murder'd.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: O, by whom?

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Those of his chamber, as it seem'd, had done 't:

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Their hands and faces were an badged with blood;

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: So were their daggers, which unwiped we found

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Upon their pillows:

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: They stared, and were distracted; no man's life

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Was to be trusted with them.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: O, yet I do repent me of my fury,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That I did kill them.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Wherefore did you so?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Who can be wise, amazed, temperate and furious,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Loyal and neutral, in a moment? No man:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The expedition my violent love

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Outrun the pauser, reason. Here lay Duncan,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: His silver skin laced with his golden blood;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And his gash'd stabs look'd like a breach in nature

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: For ruin's wasteful entrance: there, the murderers,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Steep'd in the colours of their trade, their daggers

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Unmannerly breech'd with gore: who could refrain,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That had a heart to love, and in that heart

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Courage to make 's love known?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Help me hence, ho!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Look to the lady.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Why do we hold our tongues,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That most may claim this argument for ours?

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: What should be spoken here,

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: where our fate,

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: Hid in an auger-hole, may rush, and seize us?

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: Let 's away;

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: Our tears are not yet brew'd.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Nor our strong sorrow

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Upon the foot of motion.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Look to the lady:

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: And when we have our naked frailties hid,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: That suffer in exposure, let us meet,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: And question this most bloody piece of work,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: To know it further. Fears and scruples shake us:

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: In the great hand of God I stand; and thence

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Against the undivulged pretence I fight

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Of treasonous malice.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And so do I.

Speaker: ALL
Text: So all.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Let's briefly put on manly readiness,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And meet i' the hall together.

Speaker: ALL
Text: Well contented.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: What will you do?

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Let's not consort with them:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: To show an unfelt sorrow is an office

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Which the false man does easy. I'll to England.

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: To Ireland, I; our separated fortune

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: Shall keep us both the safer: where we are,

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: There's daggers in men's smiles: the near in blood,

Speaker: DONALBAIN
Text: The nearer bloody.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: This murderous shaft that's shot

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Hath not yet lighted, and our safest way

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Is to avoid the aim. Therefore, to horse;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: And let us not be dainty of leave-taking,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: But shift away: there's warrant in that theft

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Which steals itself, when there's no mercy left.

Speaker: Old Man
Text: Threescore and ten I can remember well:

Speaker: Old Man
Text: Within the volume of which time I have seen

Speaker: Old Man
Text: Hours dreadful and things strange; but this sore night

Speaker: Old Man
Text: Hath trifled former knowings.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Ah, good father,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Thou seest, the heavens, as troubled with man's act,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Threaten his bloody stage: by the clock, 'tis day,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: And yet dark night strangles the travelling lamp:

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Is't night's predominance, or the day's shame,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: That darkness does the face of earth entomb,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: When living light should kiss it?

Speaker: Old Man
Text: 'Tis unnatural,

Speaker: Old Man
Text: Even like the deed that's done. On Tuesday last,

Speaker: Old Man
Text: A falcon, towering in her pride of place,

Speaker: Old Man
Text: Was by a mousing owl hawk'd at and kill'd.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: And Duncan's horses--a thing most strange and certain--

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Beauteous and swift, the minions of their race,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Turn'd wild in nature, broke their stalls, flung out,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Contending 'gainst obedience, as they would make

Speaker: ROSS
Text: War with mankind.

Speaker: Old Man
Text: 'Tis said they eat each other.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: They did so, to the amazement of mine eyes

Speaker: ROSS
Text: That look'd upon't. Here comes the good Macduff.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: How goes the world, sir, now?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Why, see you not?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Is't known who did this more than bloody deed?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Those that Macbeth hath slain.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Alas, the day!

Speaker: ROSS
Text: What good could they pretend?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: They were suborn'd:

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Malcolm and Donalbain, the king's two sons,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Are stol'n away and fled; which puts upon them

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Suspicion of the deed.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: 'Gainst nature still!

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Thriftless ambition, that wilt ravin up

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Thine own life's means! Then 'tis most like

Speaker: ROSS
Text: The sovereignty will fall upon Macbeth.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: He is already named, and gone to Scone

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: To be invested.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Where is Duncan's body?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Carried to Colmekill,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The sacred storehouse of his predecessors,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And guardian of their bones.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Will you to Scone?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: No, cousin, I'll to Fife.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Well, I will thither.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Well, may you see things well done there: adieu!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Lest our old robes sit easier than our new!

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Farewell, father.

Speaker: Old Man
Text: God's benison go with you; and with those

Speaker: Old Man
Text: That would make good of bad, and friends of foes!

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Thou hast it now: king, Cawdor, Glamis, all,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: As the weird women promised, and, I fear,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Thou play'dst most foully for't: yet it was said

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: It should not stand in thy posterity,

Speaker: BANQUO

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Of many kings. If there come truth from them--

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: As upon thee, Macbeth, their speeches shine--

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Why, by the verities on thee made good,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: May they not be my oracles as well,

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: And set me up in hope? But hush! no more.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Here's our chief guest.

Text: To-night we hold a solemn supper sir,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And I'll request your presence.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Let your highness

Text: Command upon me; to the which my duties

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Are with a most indissoluble tie

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: For ever knit.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Ride you this afternoon?

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: Ay, my good lord.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: We should have else desired your good advice,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Which still hath been both grave and prosperous,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: In this day's council; but we'll take to-morrow.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Is't far you ride?

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: As far, my lord, as will fill up the time

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: 'Twixt this and supper: go not my horse the better,

Speaker: BANQUO

Speaker: BANQUO

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Fail not our feast.

Speaker: BANQUO
Text: My lord, I will not.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: We hear, our bloody cousins are bestow'd

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: In England and in Ireland, not confessing

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Their cruel parricide, filling their hearers

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: With strange invention: but of that to-morrow,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: When therewithal we shall have cause of state

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Craving us jointly. Hie you to horse: adieu,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Till you return at night. Goes Fleance with you?

Speaker: BANQUO

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I wish your horses swift and sure of foot;

Text: And so I do commend you to their backs. Farewell.

Text: Let every man be master of his time

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Till seven at night: to make society

Text: The sweeter welcome, we will keep ourself

Text: Our pleasure?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Bring them before us.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To be thus is nothing; (Soliloquy Analysis)

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But to be safely thus.--Our fears in Banquo

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Stick deep; and in his royalty of nature

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Reigns that which would be fear'd: 'tis much he dares;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And, to that dauntless temper of his mind,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: He hath a wisdom that doth guide his valour

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To act in safety. There is none but he

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Whose being I do fear: and, under him,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: My Genius is rebuked; as, it is said,

Text: Upon my head they placed a fruitless crown,

Speaker: MACBETH

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thence to be wrench'd with an unlineal hand,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: No son of mine succeeding. If 't be so,

Text: For Banquo's issue have I filed my mind;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: For them the gracious Duncan have I murder'd;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Put rancours in the vessel of my peace

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Only for them; and mine eternal jewel

Text: Given to the common enemy of man,

Text: To make them kings, the seed of Banquo kings!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Rather than so, come fate into the list.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And champion me to the utterance! Who's there!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Now go to the door, and stay there till we call.

Text: Was it not yesterday we spoke together?

Text: Our point of second meeting. Do you find

Text: As hounds and greyhounds, mongrels, spaniels, curs,

Text: Distinguishes the swift, the slow, the subtle,

Text: Hath in him closed; whereby he does receive

Text: Particular addition. from the bill

Text: Now, if you have a station in the file,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Not i' the worst rank of manhood, say 't;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And I will put that business in your bosoms,

Text: Whose execution takes your enemy off,

Text: Whom the vile blows and buffets of the world

Text: Have so incensed that I am reckless what

Text: That I would set my lie on any chance,

Text: Both of you

Text: Know Banquo was your enemy.

Speaker: Both Murderers

Text: That every minute of his being thrusts

Text: Acquaint you with the perfect spy o' the time,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The moment on't; for't must be done to-night,

Text: And something from the palace; always thought

Text: Of that dark hour. Resolve yourselves apart:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I'll call upon you straight: abide within.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: It is concluded. Banquo, thy soul's flight,

Speaker: Servant
Text: Ay, madam, but returns again to-night.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: For a few words.

Speaker: Servant
Text: Madam, I will.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Nought's had, all's spent,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Where our desire is got without content:

Text: How now, my lord! why do you keep alone,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Ere we will eat our meal in fear and sleep

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: In the affliction of these terrible dreams

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That shake us nightly: better be with the dead,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Whom we, to gain our peace, have sent to peace,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Than on the torture of the mind to lie

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: In restless ecstasy. Duncan is in his grave;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: After life's fitful fever he sleeps well;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Treason has done his worst: nor steel, nor poison,

Speaker: MACBETH

Speaker: MACBETH

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Come on;

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Gentle my lord, sleek o'er your rugged looks;

Speaker: MACBETH

Speaker: MACBETH

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Unsafe the while, that we

Speaker: MACBETH

Speaker: MACBETH

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: You must leave this.

Speaker: MACBETH

Text: And now about the cauldron sing,
