Text: Live elves and fairies in a ring,

Speaker: HECATE
Text: Enchanting all that you put in.

Speaker: Second Witch
Text: By the pricking of my thumbs,

Speaker: Second Witch
Text: Something wicked this way comes.

Speaker: Second Witch
Text: Open, locks,

Speaker: Second Witch
Text: Whoever knocks!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: How now, you secret, black, and midnight hags!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What is't you do?

Speaker: ALL
Text: A deed without a name.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I conjure you, by that which you profess,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Howe'er you come to know it, answer me:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Though you untie the winds and let them fight

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Against the churches; though the yesty waves

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Confound and swallow navigation up;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Though bladed corn be lodged and trees blown down;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Though castles topple on their warders' heads;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Though palaces and pyramids do slope

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Their heads to their foundations; though the treasure

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Of nature's germens tumble all together,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Even till destruction sicken; answer me

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To what I ask you.

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Speak.

Speaker: Second Witch
Text: Demand.

Speaker: Third Witch
Text: We'll answer.

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Say, if thou'dst rather hear it from our mouths,

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Or from our masters?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Call 'em; let me see 'em.

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Pour in sow's blood, that hath eaten

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Her nine farrow; grease that's sweaten

Speaker: First Witch
Text: From the murderer's gibbet throw

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Into the flame.

Speaker: ALL
Text: Come, high or low;

Speaker: ALL
Text: Thyself and office deftly show!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Tell me, thou unknown power,--

Speaker: First Witch
Text: He knows thy thought:

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Hear his speech, but say thou nought.

Speaker: First Apparition
Text: Macbeth! Macbeth! Macbeth! beware Macduff;

Speaker: First Apparition
Text: Beware the thane of Fife. Dismiss me. Enough.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Whate'er thou art, for thy good caution, thanks;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thou hast harp'd my fear aright: but one

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: word more,--

Speaker: First Witch
Text: He will not be commanded: here's another,

Speaker: First Witch
Text: More potent than the first.

Speaker: Second Apparition
Text: Macbeth! Macbeth! Macbeth!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Had I three ears, I'ld hear thee.

Speaker: Second Apparition
Text: Be bloody, bold, and resolute; laugh to scorn

Speaker: Second Apparition
Text: The power of man, for none of woman born

Speaker: Second Apparition
Text: Shall harm Macbeth.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Then live, Macduff: what need I fear of thee?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But yet I'll make assurance double sure,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And take a bond of fate: thou shalt not live;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That I may tell pale-hearted fear it lies,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And sleep in spite of thunder.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What is this

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That rises like the issue of a king,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And wears upon his baby-brow the round

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And top of sovereignty?

Speaker: ALL
Text: Listen, but speak not to't.

Speaker: Third Apparition
Text: Be lion-mettled, proud; and take no care

Speaker: Third Apparition
Text: Who chafes, who frets, or where conspirers are:

Speaker: Third Apparition
Text: Macbeth shall never vanquish'd be until

Speaker: Third Apparition
Text: Great Birnam wood to high Dunsinane hill

Speaker: Third Apparition
Text: Shall come against him.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That will never be

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Who can impress the forest, bid the tree

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Unfix his earth-bound root? Sweet bodements! good!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Rebellion's head, rise never till the wood

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Of Birnam rise, and our high-placed Macbeth

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Shall live the lease of nature, pay his breath

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To time and mortal custom. Yet my heart

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Throbs to know one thing: tell me, if your art

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Can tell so much: shall Banquo's issue ever

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Reign in this kingdom?

Speaker: ALL
Text: Seek to know no more.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I will be satisfied: deny me this,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And an eternal curse fall on you! Let me know.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Why sinks that cauldron? and what noise is this?

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Show!

Speaker: Second Witch
Text: Show!

Speaker: Third Witch
Text: Show!

Speaker: ALL
Text: Show his eyes, and grieve his heart;

Speaker: ALL
Text: Come like shadows, so depart!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thou art too like the spirit of Banquo: down!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thy crown does sear mine eye-balls. And thy hair,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thou other gold-bound brow, is like the first.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: A third is like the former. Filthy hags!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Why do you show me this? A fourth! Start, eyes!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What, will the line stretch out to the crack of doom?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Another yet! A seventh! I'll see no more:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And yet the eighth appears, who bears a glass

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Which shows me many more; and some I see

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That two-fold balls and treble scepters carry:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Horrible sight! Now, I see, 'tis true;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: For the blood-bolter'd Banquo smiles upon me,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And points at them for his.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What, is this so?

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Ay, sir, all this is so: but why

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Stands Macbeth thus amazedly?

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Come, sisters, cheer we up his sprites,

Speaker: First Witch
Text: And show the best of our delights:

Speaker: First Witch
Text: I'll charm the air to give a sound,

Speaker: First Witch
Text: While you perform your antic round:

Speaker: First Witch
Text: That this great king may kindly say,

Speaker: First Witch
Text: Our duties did his welcome pay.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Where are they? Gone? Let this pernicious hour

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Stand aye accursed in the calendar!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Come in, without there!

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: What's your grace's will?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Saw you the weird sisters?

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: No, my lord.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Came they not by you?

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: No, indeed, my lord.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Infected be the air whereon they ride;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And damn'd all those that trust them! I did hear

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The galloping of horse: who was't came by?

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: 'Tis two or three, my lord, that bring you word

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Macduff is fled to England.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Fled to England!

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Ay, my good lord.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Time, thou anticipatest my dread exploits:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The flighty purpose never is o'ertook

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Unless the deed go with it; from this moment

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The very firstlings of my heart shall be

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The firstlings of my hand. And even now,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To crown my thoughts with acts, be it thought and done:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The castle of Macduff I will surprise;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Seize upon Fife; give to the edge o' the sword

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: His wife, his babes, and all unfortunate souls

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That trace him in his line. No boasting like a fool;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: This deed I'll do before this purpose cool.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But no more sights!--Where are these gentlemen?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Come, bring me where they are.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: What had he done, to make him fly the land?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: You must have patience, madam.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: He had none:

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: His flight was madness: when our actions do not,

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Our fears do make us traitors.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: You know not

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Whether it was his wisdom or his fear.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Wisdom! to leave his wife, to leave his babes,

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: His mansion and his titles in a place

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: From whence himself does fly? He loves us not;

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: He wants the natural touch: for the poor wren,

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: The most diminutive of birds, will fight,

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Her young ones in her nest, against the owl.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: All is the fear and nothing is the love;

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: As little is the wisdom, where the flight

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: So runs against all reason.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: My dearest coz,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: I pray you, school yourself: but for your husband,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: He is noble, wise, judicious, and best knows

Speaker: ROSS
Text: The fits o' the season. I dare not speak

Speaker: ROSS
Text: much further;

Speaker: ROSS
Text: But cruel are the times, when we are traitors

Speaker: ROSS
Text: And do not know ourselves, when we hold rumour

Speaker: ROSS
Text: From what we fear, yet know not what we fear,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: But float upon a wild and violent sea

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Each way and move. I take my leave of you:

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Shall not be long but I'll be here again:

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Things at the worst will cease, or else climb upward

Speaker: ROSS
Text: To what they were before. My pretty cousin,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Blessing upon you!

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Father'd he is, and yet he's fatherless.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: I am so much a fool, should I stay longer,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: It would be my disgrace and your discomfort:

Speaker: ROSS
Text: I take my leave at once.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Sirrah, your father's dead;

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: And what will you do now? How will you live?

Speaker: Son
Text: As birds do, mother.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: What, with worms and flies?

Speaker: Son
Text: With what I get, I mean; and so do they.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Poor bird! thou'ldst never fear the net nor lime,

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: The pitfall nor the gin.

Speaker: Son
Text: Why should I, mother? Poor birds they are not set for.

Speaker: Son
Text: My father is not dead, for all your saying.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Yes, he is dead; how wilt thou do for a father?

Speaker: Son
Text: Nay, how will you do for a husband?

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Why, I can buy me twenty at any market.

Speaker: Son
Text: Then you'll buy 'em to sell again.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Thou speak'st with all thy wit: and yet, i' faith,

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: With wit enough for thee.

Speaker: Son
Text: Was my father a traitor, mother?

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Ay, that he was.

Speaker: Son
Text: What is a traitor?

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Why, one that swears and lies.

Speaker: Son
Text: And be all traitors that do so?

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Every one that does so is a traitor, and must be hanged.

Speaker: Son
Text: And must they all be hanged that swear and lie?

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Every one.

Speaker: Son
Text: Who must hang them?

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Why, the honest men.

Speaker: Son
Text: Then the liars and swearers are fools,

Speaker: Son
Text: for there are liars and swearers enow to beat

Speaker: Son
Text: the honest men and hang up them.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Now, God help thee, poor monkey!

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: But how wilt thou do for a father?

Speaker: Son
Text: If he were dead, you'ld weep for

Speaker: Son
Text: him: if you would not, it were a good sign

Speaker: Son
Text: that I should quickly have a new father.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Poor prattler, how thou talk'st!

Speaker: Messenger
Text: Bless you, fair dame! I am not to you known,

Speaker: Messenger
Text: Though in your state of honour I am perfect.

Speaker: Messenger
Text: I doubt some danger does approach you nearly:

Speaker: Messenger
Text: If you will take a homely man's advice,

Speaker: Messenger
Text: Be not found here; hence, with your little ones.

Speaker: Messenger
Text: To fright you thus, methinks, I am too savage;

Speaker: Messenger
Text: To do worse to you were fell cruelty,

Speaker: Messenger
Text: Which is too nigh your person. Heaven preserve you!

Speaker: Messenger
Text: I dare abide no longer.

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Whither should I fly?

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: I have done no harm. But I remember now

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: I am in this earthly world; where to do harm

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Is often laudable, to do good sometime

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Accounted dangerous folly: why then, alas,

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Do I put up that womanly defence,

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: To say I have done no harm?

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: What are these faces?

Speaker: First Murderer
Text: Where is your husband?

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: I hope, in no place so unsanctified

Speaker: LADY MACDUFF
Text: Where such as thou mayst find him.

Speaker: First Murderer
Text: He's a traitor.

Speaker: Son
Text: Thou liest, thou shag-hair'd villain!

Speaker: First Murderer
Text: What, you egg!

Speaker: First Murderer
Text: Young fry of treachery!

Speaker: Son
Text: He has kill'd me, mother:

Speaker: Son
Text: Run away, I pray you!

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Let us seek out some desolate shade, and there

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Weep our sad bosoms empty.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Let us rather

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Hold fast the mortal sword, and like good men

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Bestride our down-fall'n birthdom: each new morn

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: New widows howl, new orphans cry, new sorrows

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Strike heaven on the face, that it resounds

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: As if it felt with Scotland and yell'd out

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Like syllable of dolour.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: What I believe I'll wail,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: What know believe, and what I can redress,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: As I shall find the time to friend, I will.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: What you have spoke, it may be so perchance.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: This tyrant, whose sole name blisters our tongues,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Was once thought honest: you have loved him well.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: He hath not touch'd you yet. I am young;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: but something

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: You may deserve of him through me, and wisdom

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: To offer up a weak poor innocent lamb

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: To appease an angry god.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I am not treacherous.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: But Macbeth is.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: A good and virtuous nature may recoil

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: In an imperial charge. But I shall crave

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: your pardon;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That which you are my thoughts cannot transpose:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Angels are bright still, though the brightest fell;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Though all things foul would wear the brows of grace,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Yet grace must still look so.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I have lost my hopes.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Perchance even there where I did find my doubts.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Why in that rawness left you wife and child,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Those precious motives, those strong knots of love,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Without leave-taking? I pray you,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Let not my jealousies be your dishonours,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: But mine own safeties. You may be rightly just,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Whatever I shall think.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Bleed, bleed, poor country!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Great tyranny! lay thou thy basis sure,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: For goodness dare not cheque thee: wear thou

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: thy wrongs;

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The title is affeer'd! Fare thee well, lord:

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I would not be the villain that thou think'st

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: For the whole space that's in the tyrant's grasp,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And the rich East to boot.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Be not offended:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I speak not as in absolute fear of you.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I think our country sinks beneath the yoke;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: It weeps, it bleeds; and each new day a gash

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Is added to her wounds: I think withal

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: There would be hands uplifted in my right;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: And here from gracious England have I offer

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Of goodly thousands: but, for all this,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: When I shall tread upon the tyrant's head,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Or wear it on my sword, yet my poor country

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Shall have more vices than it had before,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: More suffer and more sundry ways than ever,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: By him that shall succeed.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: What should he be?

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: It is myself I mean: in whom I know

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: All the particulars of vice so grafted

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That, when they shall be open'd, black Macbeth

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Will seem as pure as snow, and the poor state

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Esteem him as a lamb, being compared

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: With my confineless harms.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Not in the legions

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Of horrid hell can come a devil more damn'd

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: In evils to top Macbeth.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I grant him bloody,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Luxurious, avaricious, false, deceitful,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Sudden, malicious, smacking of every sin

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That has a name: but there's no bottom, none,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: In my voluptuousness: your wives, your daughters,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Your matrons and your maids, could not fill up

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: The cistern of my lust, and my desire

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: All continent impediments would o'erbear

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That did oppose my will: better Macbeth

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Than such an one to reign.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Boundless intemperance

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: In nature is a tyranny; it hath been

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The untimely emptying of the happy throne

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And fall of many kings. But fear not yet

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: To take upon you what is yours: you may

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Convey your pleasures in a spacious plenty,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And yet seem cold, the time you may so hoodwink.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: We have willing dames enough: there cannot be

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: That vulture in you, to devour so many

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: As will to greatness dedicate themselves,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Finding it so inclined.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: With this there grows

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: In my most ill-composed affection such

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: A stanchless avarice that, were I king,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I should cut off the nobles for their lands,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Desire his jewels and this other's house:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: And my more-having would be as a sauce

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: To make me hunger more; that I should forge

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Quarrels unjust against the good and loyal,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Destroying them for wealth.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: This avarice

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Sticks deeper, grows with more pernicious root

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Than summer-seeming lust, and it hath been

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The sword of our slain kings: yet do not fear;

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Scotland hath foisons to fill up your will.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Of your mere own: all these are portable,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: With other graces weigh'd.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: But I have none: the king-becoming graces,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: As justice, verity, temperance, stableness,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Bounty, perseverance, mercy, lowliness,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Devotion, patience, courage, fortitude,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I have no relish of them, but abound

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: In the division of each several crime,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Acting it many ways. Nay, had I power, I should

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Pour the sweet milk of concord into hell,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Uproar the universal peace, confound

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: All unity on earth.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: O Scotland, Scotland!

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: If such a one be fit to govern, speak:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I am as I have spoken.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Fit to govern!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: No, not to live. O nation miserable,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: With an untitled tyrant bloody-scepter'd,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: When shalt thou see thy wholesome days again,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Since that the truest issue of thy throne

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: By his own interdiction stands accursed,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And does blaspheme his breed? Thy royal father

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Was a most sainted king: the queen that bore thee,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Oftener upon her knees than on her feet,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Died every day she lived. Fare thee well!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: These evils thou repeat'st upon thyself

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Have banish'd me from Scotland. O my breast,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Thy hope ends here!

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Macduff, this noble passion,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Child of integrity, hath from my soul

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Wiped the black scruples, reconciled my thoughts

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: To thy good truth and honour. Devilish Macbeth

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: By many of these trains hath sought to win me

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Into his power, and modest wisdom plucks me

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: From over-credulous haste: but God above

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Deal between thee and me! for even now

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I put myself to thy direction, and

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Unspeak mine own detraction, here abjure

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: The taints and blames I laid upon myself,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: For strangers to my nature. I am yet

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Unknown to woman, never was forsworn,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Scarcely have coveted what was mine own,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: At no time broke my faith, would not betray

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: The devil to his fellow and delight

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: No less in truth than life: my first false speaking

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Was this upon myself: what I am truly,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Is thine and my poor country's to command:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Whither indeed, before thy here-approach,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Old Siward, with ten thousand warlike men,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Already at a point, was setting forth.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Now we'll together; and the chance of goodness

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Be like our warranted quarrel! Why are you silent?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Such welcome and unwelcome things at once

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: 'Tis hard to reconcile.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Well; more anon.--Comes the king forth, I pray you?

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Ay, sir; there are a crew of wretched souls

Speaker: Doctor
Text: That stay his cure: their malady convinces

Speaker: Doctor
Text: The great assay of art; but at his touch--

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Such sanctity hath heaven given his hand--

Speaker: Doctor
Text: They presently amend.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I thank you, doctor.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: What's the disease he means?

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: 'Tis call'd the evil:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: A most miraculous work in this good king;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Which often, since my here-remain in England,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I have seen him do. How he solicits heaven,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Himself best knows: but strangely-visited people,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: All swoln and ulcerous, pitiful to the eye,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: The mere despair of surgery, he cures,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Hanging a golden stamp about their necks,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Put on with holy prayers: and 'tis spoken,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: To the succeeding royalty he leaves

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: The healing benediction. With this strange virtue,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: He hath a heavenly gift of prophecy,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: And sundry blessings hang about his throne,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That speak him full of grace.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: See, who comes here?

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: My countryman; but yet I know him not.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: My ever-gentle cousin, welcome hither.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I know him now. Good God, betimes remove

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: The means that makes us strangers!

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Sir, amen.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Stands Scotland where it did?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Alas, poor country!

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Almost afraid to know itself. It cannot

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Be call'd our mother, but our grave; where nothing,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: But who knows nothing, is once seen to smile;

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Where sighs and groans and shrieks that rend the air

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Are made, not mark'd; where violent sorrow seems

Speaker: ROSS
Text: A modern ecstasy; the dead man's knell

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Is there scarce ask'd for who; and good men's lives

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Expire before the flowers in their caps,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Dying or ere they sicken.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: O, relation

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Too nice, and yet too true!

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: What's the newest grief?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: That of an hour's age doth hiss the speaker:

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Each minute teems a new one.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: How does my wife?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Why, well.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And all my children?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Well too.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The tyrant has not batter'd at their peace?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: No; they were well at peace when I did leave 'em.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: But not a niggard of your speech: how goes't?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: When I came hither to transport the tidings,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Which I have heavily borne, there ran a rumour

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Of many worthy fellows that were out;

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Which was to my belief witness'd the rather,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: For that I saw the tyrant's power a-foot:

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Now is the time of help; your eye in Scotland

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Would create soldiers, make our women fight,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: To doff their dire distresses.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Be't their comfort

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: We are coming thither: gracious England hath

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Lent us good Siward and ten thousand men;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: An older and a better soldier none

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That Christendom gives out.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Would I could answer

Speaker: ROSS
Text: This comfort with the like! But I have words

Speaker: ROSS
Text: That would be howl'd out in the desert air,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Where hearing should not latch them.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: What concern they?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The general cause? or is it a fee-grief

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Due to some single breast?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: No mind that's honest

Speaker: ROSS
Text: But in it shares some woe; though the main part

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Pertains to you alone.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: If it be mine,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Keep it not from me, quickly let me have it.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Let not your ears despise my tongue for ever,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Which shall possess them with the heaviest sound

Speaker: ROSS
Text: That ever yet they heard.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Hum! I guess at it.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Your castle is surprised; your wife and babes

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Savagely slaughter'd: to relate the manner,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Were, on the quarry of these murder'd deer,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: To add the death of you.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Merciful heaven!

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: What, man! ne'er pull your hat upon your brows;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Give sorrow words: the grief that does not speak

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Whispers the o'er-fraught heart and bids it break.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: My children too?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Wife, children, servants, all

Speaker: ROSS
Text: That could be found.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And I must be from thence!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: My wife kill'd too?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: I have said.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Be comforted:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Let's make us medicines of our great revenge,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: To cure this deadly grief.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: He has no children. All my pretty ones?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Did you say all? O hell-kite! All?

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: What, all my pretty chickens and their dam

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: At one fell swoop?

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Dispute it like a man.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I shall do so;

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: But I must also feel it as a man:

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I cannot but remember such things were,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: That were most precious to me. Did heaven look on,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And would not take their part? Sinful Macduff,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: They were all struck for thee! naught that I am,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Not for their own demerits, but for mine,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Fell slaughter on their souls. Heaven rest them now!

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Be this the whetstone of your sword: let grief

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Convert to anger; blunt not the heart, enrage it.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: O, I could play the woman with mine eyes

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And braggart with my tongue! But, gentle heavens,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Cut short all intermission; front to front

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Bring thou this fiend of Scotland and myself;

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Within my sword's length set him; if he 'scape,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Heaven forgive him too!

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: This tune goes manly.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Come, go we to the king; our power is ready;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Our lack is nothing but our leave; Macbeth

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Is ripe for shaking, and the powers above

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Put on their instruments. Receive what cheer you may:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: The night is long that never finds the day.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: I have two nights watched with you, but can perceive

Speaker: Doctor
Text: no truth in your report. When was it she last walked?

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: Since his majesty went into the field, I have seen

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: her rise from her bed, throw her night-gown upon

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: her, unlock her closet, take forth paper, fold it,

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: write upon't, read it, afterwards seal it, and again

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: return to bed; yet all this while in a most fast sleep.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: A great perturbation in nature, to receive at once

Speaker: Doctor
Text: the benefit of sleep, and do the effects of

Speaker: Doctor
Text: watching! In this slumbery agitation, besides her

Speaker: Doctor
Text: walking and other actual performances, what, at any

Speaker: Doctor
Text: time, have you heard her say?

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: That, sir, which I will not report after her.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: You may to me: and 'tis most meet you should.

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: Neither to you nor any one; having no witness to

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: confirm my speech.

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: Lo you, here she comes! This is her very guise;

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: and, upon my life, fast asleep. Observe her; stand close.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: How came she by that light?

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: Why, it stood by her: she has light by her

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: continually; 'tis her command.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: You see, her eyes are open.

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: Ay, but their sense is shut.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: What is it she does now? Look, how she rubs her hands.

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: It is an accustomed action with her, to seem thus

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: washing her hands: I have known her continue in

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: this a quarter of an hour.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Yet here's a spot.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Hark! she speaks: I will set down what comes from

Speaker: Doctor
Text: her, to satisfy my remembrance the more strongly.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Out, damned spot! out, I say!--One: two: why,

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: then, 'tis time to do't.--Hell is murky!--Fie, my

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: lord, fie! a soldier, and afeard? What need we

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: fear who knows it, when none can call our power to

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: account?--Yet who would have thought the old man

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: to have had so much blood in him.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Do you mark that?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: The thane of Fife had a wife: where is she now?--

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: What, will these hands ne'er be clean?--No more o'

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: that, my lord, no more o' that: you mar all with

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: this starting.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Go to, go to; you have known what you should not.

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: She has spoke what she should not, I am sure of

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: that: heaven knows what she has known.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Here's the smell of the blood still: all the

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: perfumes of Arabia will not sweeten this little

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: hand. Oh, oh, oh!

Speaker: Doctor
Text: What a sigh is there! The heart is sorely charged.

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: I would not have such a heart in my bosom for the

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: dignity of the whole body.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Well, well, well,--

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: Pray God it be, sir.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: This disease is beyond my practise: yet I have known

Speaker: Doctor
Text: those which have walked in their sleep who have died

Speaker: Doctor
Text: holily in their beds.

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: Wash your hands, put on your nightgown; look not so

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: pale.--I tell you yet again, Banquo's buried; he

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: cannot come out on's grave.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Even so?

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: To bed, to bed! there's knocking at the gate:

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: come, come, come, come, give me your hand. What's

Speaker: LADY MACBETH
Text: done cannot be undone.--To bed, to bed, to bed!

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Will she go now to bed?

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: Directly.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Foul whisperings are abroad: unnatural deeds

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Do breed unnatural troubles: infected minds

Speaker: Doctor
Text: To their deaf pillows will discharge their secrets:

Speaker: Doctor
Text: More needs she the divine than the physician.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: God, God forgive us all! Look after her;

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Remove from her the means of all annoyance,

Speaker: Doctor
Text: And still keep eyes upon her. So, good night:

Speaker: Doctor
Text: My mind she has mated, and amazed my sight.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: I think, but dare not speak.

Speaker: Gentlewoman
Text: Good night, good doctor.

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: The English power is near, led on by Malcolm,

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: His uncle Siward and the good Macduff:

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: Revenges burn in them; for their dear causes

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: Would to the bleeding and the grim alarm

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: Excite the mortified man.

Speaker: ANGUS
Text: Near Birnam wood

Speaker: ANGUS
Text: Shall we well meet them; that way are they coming.

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: Who knows if Donalbain be with his brother?

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: For certain, sir, he is not: I have a file

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Of all the gentry: there is Siward's son,

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: And many unrough youths that even now

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Protest their first of manhood.

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: What does the tyrant?

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: Great Dunsinane he strongly fortifies:

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: Some say he's mad; others that lesser hate him

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: Do call it valiant fury: but, for certain,

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: He cannot buckle his distemper'd cause

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: Within the belt of rule.

Speaker: ANGUS
Text: Now does he feel

Speaker: ANGUS
Text: His secret murders sticking on his hands;

Speaker: ANGUS
Text: Now minutely revolts upbraid his faith-breach;

Speaker: ANGUS
Text: Those he commands move only in command,

Speaker: ANGUS
Text: Nothing in love: now does he feel his title

Speaker: ANGUS
Text: Hang loose about him, like a giant's robe

Speaker: ANGUS
Text: Upon a dwarfish thief.

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: Who then shall blame

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: His pester'd senses to recoil and start,

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: When all that is within him does condemn

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: Itself for being there?

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: Well, march we on,

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: To give obedience where 'tis truly owed:

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: Meet we the medicine of the sickly weal,

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: And with him pour we in our country's purge

Speaker: CAITHNESS
Text: Each drop of us.

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Or so much as it needs,

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: To dew the sovereign flower and drown the weeds.

Speaker: LENNOX
Text: Make we our march towards Birnam.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Bring me no more reports; let them fly all:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Till Birnam wood remove to Dunsinane,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I cannot taint with fear. What's the boy Malcolm?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Was he not born of woman? The spirits that know

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: All mortal consequences have pronounced me thus:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: 'Fear not, Macbeth; no man that's born of woman

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Shall e'er have power upon thee.' Then fly,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: false thanes,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And mingle with the English epicures:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The mind I sway by and the heart I bear

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Shall never sag with doubt nor shake with fear.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The devil damn thee black, thou cream-faced loon!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Where got'st thou that goose look?

Speaker: Servant
Text: There is ten thousand--

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Geese, villain!

Speaker: Servant
Text: Soldiers, sir.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Go prick thy face, and over-red thy fear,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thou lily-liver'd boy. What soldiers, patch?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Death of thy soul! those linen cheeks of thine

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Are counsellors to fear. What soldiers, whey-face?

Speaker: Servant
Text: The English force, so please you.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Take thy face hence.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Seyton!--I am sick at heart,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: When I behold--Seyton, I say!--This push

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Will cheer me ever, or disseat me now.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I have lived long enough: my way of life

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Is fall'n into the sear, the yellow leaf,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And that which should accompany old age,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: As honour, love, obedience, troops of friends,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I must not look to have; but, in their stead,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Curses, not loud but deep, mouth-honour, breath,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Which the poor heart would fain deny, and dare not. Seyton!

Speaker: SEYTON
Text: What is your gracious pleasure?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What news more?

Speaker: SEYTON
Text: All is confirm'd, my lord, which was reported.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I'll fight till from my bones my flesh be hack'd.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Give me my armour.

Speaker: SEYTON
Text: 'Tis not needed yet.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I'll put it on.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Send out more horses; skirr the country round;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Hang those that talk of fear. Give me mine armour.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: How does your patient, doctor?

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Not so sick, my lord,

Speaker: Doctor
Text: As she is troubled with thick coming fancies,

Speaker: Doctor
Text: That keep her from her rest.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Cure her of that.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Canst thou not minister to a mind diseased,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Pluck from the memory a rooted sorrow,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Raze out the written troubles of the brain

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And with some sweet oblivious antidote

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Cleanse the stuff'd bosom of that perilous stuff

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Which weighs upon the heart?

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Therein the patient

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Must minister to himself.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Throw physic to the dogs; I'll none of it.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Come, put mine armour on; give me my staff.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Seyton, send out. Doctor, the thanes fly from me.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Come, sir, dispatch. If thou couldst, doctor, cast

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The water of my land, find her disease,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And purge it to a sound and pristine health,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I would applaud thee to the very echo,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That should applaud again.--Pull't off, I say.--

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What rhubarb, cyme, or what purgative drug,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Would scour these English hence? Hear'st thou of them?

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Ay, my good lord; your royal preparation

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Makes us hear something.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Bring it after me.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I will not be afraid of death and bane,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Till Birnam forest come to Dunsinane.

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Were I from Dunsinane away and clear,

Speaker: Doctor
Text: Profit again should hardly draw me here.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Cousins, I hope the days are near at hand

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That chambers will be safe.

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: We doubt it nothing.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: What wood is this before us?

Speaker: MENTEITH
Text: The wood of Birnam.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Let every soldier hew him down a bough

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: And bear't before him: thereby shall we shadow

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: The numbers of our host and make discovery

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Err in report of us.

Speaker: Soldiers
Text: It shall be done.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: We learn no other but the confident tyrant

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Keeps still in Dunsinane, and will endure

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Our setting down before 't.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: 'Tis his main hope:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: For where there is advantage to be given,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Both more and less have given him the revolt,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: And none serve with him but constrained things

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Whose hearts are absent too.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Let our just censures

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Attend the true event, and put we on

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Industrious soldiership.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: The time approaches

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: That will with due decision make us know

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: What we shall say we have and what we owe.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Thoughts speculative their unsure hopes relate,

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: But certain issue strokes must arbitrate:

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Towards which advance the war.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Hang out our banners on the outward walls;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The cry is still 'They come:' our castle's strength

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Will laugh a siege to scorn: here let them lie

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Till famine and the ague eat them up:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Were they not forced with those that should be ours,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: We might have met them dareful, beard to beard,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And beat them backward home.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: What is that noise?

Speaker: SEYTON
Text: It is the cry of women, my good lord.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I have almost forgot the taste of fears;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The time has been, my senses would have cool'd

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To hear a night-shriek; and my fell of hair

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Would at a dismal treatise rouse and stir

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: As life were in't: I have supp'd full with horrors;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Direness, familiar to my slaughterous thoughts

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Cannot once start me.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Wherefore was that cry?

Speaker: SEYTON
Text: The queen, my lord, is dead.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: She should have died hereafter;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: There would have been a time for such a word.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To-morrow, and to-morrow, and to-morrow,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Creeps in this petty pace from day to day

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To the last syllable of recorded time,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And all our yesterdays have lighted fools

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: The way to dusty death. Out, out, brief candle!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Life's but a walking shadow, a poor player

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That struts and frets his hour upon the stage

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And then is heard no more: it is a tale

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Told by an idiot, full of sound and fury,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Signifying nothing.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thou comest to use thy tongue; thy story quickly.

Speaker: Messenger
Text: Gracious my lord,

Speaker: Messenger
Text: I should report that which I say I saw,

Speaker: Messenger
Text: But know not how to do it.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Well, say, sir.

Speaker: Messenger
Text: As I did stand my watch upon the hill,

Speaker: Messenger
Text: I look'd toward Birnam, and anon, methought,

Speaker: Messenger
Text: The wood began to move.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Liar and slave!

Speaker: Messenger
Text: Let me endure your wrath, if't be not so:

Speaker: Messenger
Text: Within this three mile may you see it coming;

Speaker: Messenger
Text: I say, a moving grove.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: If thou speak'st false,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Upon the next tree shalt thou hang alive,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Till famine cling thee: if thy speech be sooth,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I care not if thou dost for me as much.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I pull in resolution, and begin

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To doubt the equivocation of the fiend

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That lies like truth: 'Fear not, till Birnam wood

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Do come to Dunsinane:' and now a wood

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Comes toward Dunsinane. Arm, arm, and out!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: If this which he avouches does appear,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: There is nor flying hence nor tarrying here.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I gin to be aweary of the sun,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And wish the estate o' the world were now undone.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Ring the alarum-bell! Blow, wind! come, wrack!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: At least we'll die with harness on our back.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Now near enough: your leafy screens throw down.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: And show like those you are. You, worthy uncle,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Shall, with my cousin, your right-noble son,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Lead our first battle: worthy Macduff and we

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Shall take upon 's what else remains to do,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: According to our order.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Fare you well.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Do we but find the tyrant's power to-night,

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Let us be beaten, if we cannot fight.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Make all our trumpets speak; give them all breath,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Those clamorous harbingers of blood and death.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: They have tied me to a stake; I cannot fly,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But, bear-like, I must fight the course. What's he

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That was not born of woman? Such a one

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Am I to fear, or none.

Speaker: YOUNG SIWARD
Text: What is thy name?

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thou'lt be afraid to hear it.

Speaker: YOUNG SIWARD
Text: No; though thou call'st thyself a hotter name

Speaker: YOUNG SIWARD
Text: Than any is in hell.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: My name's Macbeth.

Speaker: YOUNG SIWARD
Text: The devil himself could not pronounce a title

Speaker: YOUNG SIWARD
Text: More hateful to mine ear.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: No, nor more fearful.

Speaker: YOUNG SIWARD
Text: Thou liest, abhorred tyrant; with my sword

Speaker: YOUNG SIWARD
Text: I'll prove the lie thou speak'st.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thou wast born of woman

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But swords I smile at, weapons laugh to scorn,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Brandish'd by man that's of a woman born.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: That way the noise is. Tyrant, show thy face!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: If thou be'st slain and with no stroke of mine,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: My wife and children's ghosts will haunt me still.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I cannot strike at wretched kerns, whose arms

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Are hired to bear their staves: either thou, Macbeth,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Or else my sword with an unbatter'd edge

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I sheathe again undeeded. There thou shouldst be;

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: By this great clatter, one of greatest note

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Seems bruited. Let me find him, fortune!

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And more I beg not.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: This way, my lord; the castle's gently render'd:

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: The tyrant's people on both sides do fight;

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: The noble thanes do bravely in the war;

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: The day almost itself professes yours,

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: And little is to do.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: We have met with foes

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That strike beside us.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Enter, sir, the castle.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Why should I play the Roman fool, and die

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: On mine own sword? whiles I see lives, the gashes

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Do better upon them.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Turn, hell-hound, turn!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Of all men else I have avoided thee:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: But get thee back; my soul is too much charged

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: With blood of thine already.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I have no words:

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: My voice is in my sword: thou bloodier villain

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Than terms can give thee out!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Thou losest labour:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: As easy mayst thou the intrenchant air

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: With thy keen sword impress as make me bleed:

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Let fall thy blade on vulnerable crests;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I bear a charmed life, which must not yield,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To one of woman born.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Despair thy charm;

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And let the angel whom thou still hast served

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Tell thee, Macduff was from his mother's womb

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Untimely ripp'd.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Accursed be that tongue that tells me so,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: For it hath cow'd my better part of man!

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And be these juggling fiends no more believed,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That palter with us in a double sense;

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: That keep the word of promise to our ear,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And break it to our hope. I'll not fight with thee.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Then yield thee, coward,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: And live to be the show and gaze o' the time:

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: We'll have thee, as our rarer monsters are,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Painted on a pole, and underwrit,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: 'Here may you see the tyrant.'

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I will not yield,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: To kiss the ground before young Malcolm's feet,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And to be baited with the rabble's curse.

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Though Birnam wood be come to Dunsinane,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And thou opposed, being of no woman born,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: Yet I will try the last. Before my body

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: I throw my warlike shield. Lay on, Macduff,

Speaker: MACBETH
Text: And damn'd be him that first cries, 'Hold, enough!'

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: I would the friends we miss were safe arrived.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Some must go off: and yet, by these I see,

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: So great a day as this is cheaply bought.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Macduff is missing, and your noble son.

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Your son, my lord, has paid a soldier's debt:

Speaker: ROSS
Text: He only lived but till he was a man;

Speaker: ROSS
Text: The which no sooner had his prowess confirm'd

Speaker: ROSS
Text: In the unshrinking station where he fought,

Speaker: ROSS
Text: But like a man he died.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Then he is dead?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Ay, and brought off the field: your cause of sorrow

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Must not be measured by his worth, for then

Speaker: ROSS
Text: It hath no end.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Had he his hurts before?

Speaker: ROSS
Text: Ay, on the front.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Why then, God's soldier be he!

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: Had I as many sons as I have hairs,

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: I would not wish them to a fairer death:

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: And so, his knell is knoll'd.

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: He's worth more sorrow,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: And that I'll spend for him.

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: He's worth no more

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: They say he parted well, and paid his score:

Speaker: SIWARD
Text: And so, God be with him! Here comes newer comfort.

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Hail, king! for so thou art: behold, where stands

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: The usurper's cursed head: the time is free:

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: I see thee compass'd with thy kingdom's pearl,

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: That speak my salutation in their minds;

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Whose voices I desire aloud with mine:

Speaker: MACDUFF
Text: Hail, King of Scotland!

Speaker: ALL
Text: Hail, King of Scotland!

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: We shall not spend a large expense of time

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Before we reckon with your several loves,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: And make us even with you. My thanes and kinsmen,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Henceforth be earls, the first that ever Scotland

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: In such an honour named. What's more to do,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Which would be planted newly with the time,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: As calling home our exiled friends abroad

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That fled the snares of watchful tyranny;

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Producing forth the cruel ministers

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Of this dead butcher and his fiend-like queen,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Who, as 'tis thought, by self and violent hands

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Took off her life; this, and what needful else

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: That calls upon us, by the grace of Grace,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: We will perform in measure, time and place:

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: So, thanks to all at once and to each one,

Speaker: MALCOLM
Text: Whom we invite to see us crown'd at Scone.
